{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632996"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17457"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70885"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5344"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70885"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA community\u0027s drinking water supply shows consistently high turbidity readings. Turbidity is a measure of water cloudiness caused by suspended particles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary public health concern associated with high water turbidity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased risk of gastrointestinal illness","Increased risk of dental fluorosis","Increased risk of heavy metal poisoning","Increased risk of thyroid disease","Increased risk of skin cancer"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary health concern with high turbidity is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased risk of gastrointestinal illness\u003C/strong\u003E. Suspended particles can harbour and protect disease-causing microorganisms from disinfection processes, leading to increased transmission of waterborne pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDental fluorosis\u003C/strong\u003E relates to excessive fluoride exposure in drinking water and is not associated with turbidity levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy metal poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to specific contamination with metals such as lead or mercury, rather than from turbidity itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid disease\u003C/strong\u003E has no direct relationship with water turbidity and is more commonly associated with iodine deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily caused by ultraviolet radiation exposure and has no association with water turbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon pathogens protected by turbid water include \u003Cem\u003EGiardia lamblia\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ECryptosporidium parvum\u003C/em\u003E, and various bacteria that can cause diarrhoeal diseases. High turbidity also indicates possible contamination from surface runoff, which may contain additional disease-causing organisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["High turbidity in drinking water is associated with increased risk of gastrointestinal illness.","Turbid water can harbour and protect disease-causing organisms from disinfection.","Waterborne pathogens including Giardia and Cryptosporidium are more likely to survive in highly turbid water."],"references":["De Roos AJ, Gurian PL, Robinson LF, Rai A, Zakeri I, Kondo MC. Review of Epidemiological Studies of Drinking-Water Turbidity in Relation to Acute Gastrointestinal Illness. Environ Health Perspect. 2017;125(8):086003. Published 2017 Aug 17. doi:10.1289/EHP1090","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:57:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:58:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70885"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id